&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; Echinodermata&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size:16px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation-&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Echinoderms&lt;/strong&gt;, a group that includes sea stars (starfish), sea cucumbers, sea urchins, sand dollars, and brittle stars, possess a unique structural feature known as the water vascular system.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The water vascular system is a network of water-filled canals that function in locomotion, feeding, gas exchange, and sensory perception. Here&amp;#39;s how it generally works:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Water Inflow:&lt;/strong&gt; Seawater enters the system through a sieve-like structure on the echinoderm&amp;#39;s body surface called the&lt;strong&gt; madreporite.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stone Canal:&lt;/strong&gt; From the madreporite, water then flows into a short canal, often lined with calcareous material, known as the stone canal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ring Canal&lt;/strong&gt;: The stone canal leads to a circular canal, the ring canal, that surrounds the esophagus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Radial Canal(s):&lt;/strong&gt; Connected to the ring canal are five (or multiples of five) radial canals. These extend into each of the echinoderm&amp;#39;s arms (if arms are present).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tube Feet:&lt;/strong&gt; Off of the radial canals are many lateral canals, each terminating in a muscular, often sucker-tipped, extension known as a tube foot or podium. The sequential contraction and expansion of the tube feet, controlled by the water pressure within the canals, assist with locomotion, enable feeding, and facilitate gas exchange.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The water vascular system in echinoderms allows these marine animals to move effectively despite having no centralized brain nor discernable front or back to their bodies.&lt;/p&gt;

